      "writtenOn": "2026-06-16T16:44:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Florin - I read through the code again and i would rather not to change the current approach. Explanation: these two lines are invoked on the client_ssl_ctx object which is a singleton object per worker-thread per protocol (TLS or DTLS), and this client_ssl_ctx object is created inside function openssl_init_client_ctx() via function-call openssl_get_client_ssl_ctx() - so it lazily creates this client_ssl_ctx object for only once per each worker-thread per protocol. If we conditionally enable cache-mode and call-back function based on the enablement-state at the moment when the client_ssl_ctx is being created, then we may have to add extra logic in openssl_get_client_ssl_ctx() to conditional enable/disable the cache-mode and cb-function based on whether the cache-enablement-state has been changed since last access. To me, the current approach is simpler and better: when creating the client_ssl_ctx, we just unconditionally turn on the cache-mode and set the call-back function, however, inside the call-back function and the cache-lookup function, we do a quick check on the max-entries field in the cache object - if it\u0027s zero (meaning the caching is disabled), we\u0027ll just do a quick return without further processing",
      "parentUuid": "47fd1ee8_f50cd1b8",
      "revId": "1aaec45eed13b776445817ee059f64cd3421d9a7",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
